You could use projection to select only `name` property:
```
interface CustomerNameProjection {
   String getName();
}
```

and then use it in `Repository` class:
```
List&lt;CustomerNameProjection&gt; findAllProjectedBy();
```

edit: corrected repository method name

[Spring Data JPA][1] supports this quite well. You can define a POJO that represents the (reduced) object (the projection) you want of the entity, then [define a method that describes the query][2], returns the appropriate type, and Spring Data will generate all the code necessary to execute the query and map the results.

Here&#39;s an example of a custom repository interface that uses this technique (untested pseudo-code):

```java
public class CustomerSummary {
    private String name;
    // constructor and getters
}

@Repository
public interface CustomerRepository extends CrudRepository&lt;Customer, Long&gt; {
    List&lt;CustomerSummary&gt; getAllSummaries();
}
```

I&#39;m not sure if you can use &quot;simple&quot; types such as `String` in the return type, but I wouldn&#39;t be surprised if that is supported.

Also, you might have to tweak the exact method naming of `` to make sure Spring Data correctly interprets it as you want. [Here][3] is some additional reference documentation.


  [1]: https://spring.io/projects/spring-data-jpa
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/jpa/docs/current/reference/html/#jpa.query-methods
  [3]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/jpa/docs/current/reference/html/#repository-query-keywords

